{"body": "Step._get_match() doesn't apply any ordering to the regexs, functions returned from the STEP_REGISTRY:\r\nhttps://github.com/gabrielfalcao/lettuce/blob/master/lettuce/core.py#L302\r\n\r\nThis makes tests \"randomly\" pass/fail if you have step regexps that accidentally overlap. The worst part is adding steps without overlapping regexps changes the order steps are returned from STEP_REGISTRY.items() so unrelated steps/scenarios fail. As the number of steps increases it becomes very difficult to figure out why tests pass/fail on different developers/testers machines - we now know to look for overlapping/non-anchored regexps but it can be a painful process.\r\n\r\nIf the regexps were sorted, probably by length - longest first, then at least your tests would always pass or fail regardless of where they were run or due to the addition of some categories of non-overlapping regexps.\r\n\r\nThe quick answer is \"don't have overlapping regexps\", but on big projects they are almost inevitable... I don't mind if they overlap as long as they are always applied the same order. In fact, I'd like to use them in some circumstances (adding qualifiers to the end of step definition instead of having many \"And\" lines). \r\n\r\nI can create a patch if you are interested.", "events_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/gabrielfalcao/lettuce/issues/174/events", "updated_at": "2011-08-24T21:17:17Z", "labels_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/gabrielfalcao/lettuce/issues/174/labels{/name}", "labels": [], "comments_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/gabrielfalcao/lettuce/issues/174/comments", "html_url": "https://github.com/gabrielfalcao/lettuce/issues/174", "number": 174, "assignee": null, "user": {"following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/saschwarz/following{/other_user}", "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/saschwarz/events{/privacy}", "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/saschwarz/orgs", "url": "https://api.github.com/users/saschwarz", "gists_url":